 [Music]

2
00:00:28,000 --> 00:00:36,000
 All right, all right, all right. Porch, how we doing? Doing okay? Yes? Hey, it's great to be back with you tonight.

3
00:00:36,000 --> 00:00:41,000
 So grateful that you joined us from wherever it is you came from. I don't know if you're here from out of town,

4
00:00:41,000 --> 00:00:48,000
 if you're a regular in the room. We always have some Porch Live locations tuning in with us on Tuesday nights as well.

5
00:00:48,000 --> 00:00:54,000
 So special shout out to all of you that are tuning in with us online, especially Fresno, Scottsdale, Tulsa.

6
00:00:54,000 --> 00:00:59,000
 We love you. Thanks for being here with us. Hey, we've been in the middle of a series in the book of Colossians,

7
00:00:59,000 --> 00:01:04,000
 which we're continuing tonight, but I want to open up with an illustration, which I think may be helpful.

8
00:01:04,000 --> 00:01:12,000
 I remember starting my first job out of college and finding the experience confusing to say the least.

9
00:01:12,000 --> 00:01:16,000
 Anybody have that same experience? You jump out of college, you get into your first job, and you're like,

10
00:01:16,000 --> 00:01:20,000
 "What is happening right now? This is not at all like what I expected."

11
00:01:20,000 --> 00:01:24,000
 Let me explain to you why that was the case for me. You see, normally, when you step out of college,

12
00:01:24,000 --> 00:01:31,000
 you walk the stage, you make your way into your first job. You are in the midst of a lot of anew.

13
00:01:31,000 --> 00:01:35,000
 You've moved into a new city. You've found a new place to live.

14
00:01:35,000 --> 00:01:40,000
 You've committed to a new set of responsibilities during your week. You're trying to find new friends.

15
00:01:40,000 --> 00:01:45,000
 You're trying to understand the new landscape, a part of which you are now calling home.

16
00:01:45,000 --> 00:01:50,000
 This is the case for many of us when we step into a new job, especially out of college.

17
00:01:50,000 --> 00:01:57,000
 But this was not the case for me because I graduated and I stayed right where I was.

18
00:01:57,000 --> 00:02:03,000
 I didn't move cities. I didn't change locales. I didn't even leave the place where I was living.

19
00:02:03,000 --> 00:02:10,000
 I stayed in College Station, Texas, because I went to Texas A&M University,

20
00:02:10,000 --> 00:02:16,000
 aka the promised land. It's a holy place. Hang in there with me.

21
00:02:16,000 --> 00:02:20,000
 No, I stayed in the same city which I had spent the last four years at that time,

22
00:02:20,000 --> 00:02:28,000
 which meant that I lived a lot of the same normal regularities for me that I had lived previously.

23
00:02:28,000 --> 00:02:33,000
 I had the same roommates, and I lived in the same house, and I went to the same restaurants,

24
00:02:33,000 --> 00:02:39,000
 and I went to the same gym, and I went to the same church.

25
00:02:39,000 --> 00:02:44,000
 I was a part of all of these sames that had been a part of my story.

26
00:02:44,000 --> 00:02:49,000
 They were continuing forward for me, which sounds really great, right?

27
00:02:49,000 --> 00:02:52,000
 Man, that sounds nice. You can acclimate to a new job.

28
00:02:52,000 --> 00:02:56,000
 You can be a part of a new set of normal rhythms while also having all the same friends

29
00:02:56,000 --> 00:03:01,000
 in all the same places and all the same things, which you would think is true,

30
00:03:01,000 --> 00:03:06,000
 but was not the case for me. You see, because with a new job came a new way of life,

31
00:03:06,000 --> 00:03:10,000
 and with that new way of life came a new set of expectations.

32
00:03:10,000 --> 00:03:15,000
 You see, where the old me would choose to skip class if he wanted to—totally hypothetical—

33
00:03:15,000 --> 00:03:22,000
 the new me could not skip work. Where the old me could choose to take as many hours as he wanted for lunch,

34
00:03:22,000 --> 00:03:26,000
 the new me got one hour for lunch every single day.

35
00:03:26,000 --> 00:03:31,000
 Where the old me would look at his week and say, "Man, I don't have as much work to do as I thought."

36
00:03:31,000 --> 00:03:35,000
 The new me would look at his week and realize, "I have plenty of work to do."

37
00:03:35,000 --> 00:03:38,000
 Where the old me could spend as much time as he wanted at the gym,

38
00:03:38,000 --> 00:03:43,000
 the new me had to either get up in the morning or go at the end of the day.

39
00:03:43,000 --> 00:03:48,000
 My old rhythms did not fit with my new way of life.

40
00:03:48,000 --> 00:03:52,000
 Which sounds pretty miserable, right? You would think it's great,

41
00:03:52,000 --> 00:03:56,000
 but then you hear, "Man, you're not able to enjoy any of the same things you used to

42
00:03:56,000 --> 00:04:01,000
 because of the new way of life you're now a part of?" That sounds awful.

43
00:04:01,000 --> 00:04:06,000
 And yet, I would tell you, it was amazing. Why?

44
00:04:06,000 --> 00:04:11,000
 Because though it was disorienting, I was kind of in my old stomping grounds

45
00:04:11,000 --> 00:04:17,000
 while still living a new way of life. That new way of life was worthy of figuring out.

46
00:04:17,000 --> 00:04:23,000
 And the reason for it is because I loved everything it afforded me.

47
00:04:23,000 --> 00:04:29,000
 The opportunities it gave me to grow and the lessons it would teach me,

48
00:04:29,000 --> 00:04:32,000
 the responsibilities that were imparted to me, the money that I made,

49
00:04:32,000 --> 00:04:35,000
 the team that I joined, the company I worked for,

50
00:04:35,000 --> 00:04:37,000
 the fact that I didn't have to go to class.

51
00:04:37,000 --> 00:04:40,000
 Instead, I was entrusted with something that was meaningful.

52
00:04:40,000 --> 00:04:43,000
 I loved all of this that was now a part of my new way of life.

53
00:04:43,000 --> 00:04:45,000
 But here's the thing that you need to know.

54
00:04:45,000 --> 00:04:48,000
 I tell you that because when you step into a new way of life,

55
00:04:48,000 --> 00:04:51,000
 there are often new lessons to learn.

56
00:04:51,000 --> 00:04:55,000
 That was true for me. I wasn't able to just do the things that I had done.

57
00:04:55,000 --> 00:04:58,000
 I now had to do new things instead.

58
00:04:58,000 --> 00:05:01,000
 And that is the case for those that place their faith in Jesus Christ.

59
00:05:01,000 --> 00:05:08,000
 When you step into life with Christ, you embark upon a new chapter of life.

60
00:05:08,000 --> 00:05:10,000
 And everything changes for you.

61
00:05:10,000 --> 00:05:13,000
 Like you get new opportunities to grow.

62
00:05:13,000 --> 00:05:18,000
 You get new experiences to enjoy, community to find, responsibilities to sue.

63
00:05:18,000 --> 00:05:21,000
 You get all of this newness, which is really amazing.

64
00:05:21,000 --> 00:05:29,000
 And yet, with that new way of life, come new lessons you have to learn.

65
00:05:29,000 --> 00:05:32,000
 I tell you that because that's where we're at tonight.

66
00:05:32,000 --> 00:05:34,000
 You see, we've been journeying through the book of Colossians.

67
00:05:34,000 --> 00:05:37,000
 And as we come to chapter 2, which is where we are this evening,

68
00:05:37,000 --> 00:05:39,000
 that you can turn to right now if you want,

69
00:05:39,000 --> 00:05:43,000
 Paul is hinging from everything he's been saying,

70
00:05:43,000 --> 00:05:48,000
 pointing to, hey, this is what it looks like to walk into relationship with Jesus

71
00:05:48,000 --> 00:05:52,000
 and then walk out of that relationship as you live your life forward

72
00:05:52,000 --> 00:05:54,000
 to now talking about what's next,

73
00:05:54,000 --> 00:05:57,000
 which is important and relevant for the Colossians that he's writing to.

74
00:05:57,000 --> 00:06:00,000
 Because this group of young believers, they are asking the question,

75
00:06:00,000 --> 00:06:02,000
 we've placed our faith in Jesus.

76
00:06:02,000 --> 00:06:04,000
 We understand everything you're saying, Paul.

77
00:06:04,000 --> 00:06:06,000
 But now what? We want to move forward.

78
00:06:06,000 --> 00:06:09,000
 We want to mature in our spirituality.

79
00:06:09,000 --> 00:06:11,000
 We want to advance. We want to take new ground.

80
00:06:11,000 --> 00:06:15,000
 We want to get better, which may feel like you.

81
00:06:15,000 --> 00:06:17,000
 You've been walking with Jesus.

82
00:06:17,000 --> 00:06:21,000
 Maybe you've just recently started investigating the person of Christ

83
00:06:21,000 --> 00:06:23,000
 and you're trying to evaluate for yourself.

84
00:06:23,000 --> 00:06:27,000
 Okay, I'm kind of into this. I believe in him even.

85
00:06:27,000 --> 00:06:29,000
 But where do I go from here?

86
00:06:29,000 --> 00:06:32,000
 This is the question the Colossians are asking as well.

87
00:06:32,000 --> 00:06:35,000
 They want to know what it looks like to not just be as they are,

88
00:06:35,000 --> 00:06:40,000
 but to become everything that God wants them to be.

89
00:06:40,000 --> 00:06:42,000
 And so Paul, he moves into chapter 2

90
00:06:42,000 --> 00:06:46,000
 and he starts to write to them a series of lessons they need to learn.

91
00:06:46,000 --> 00:06:49,000
 And he's doing so to refute a lot of the lessons

92
00:06:49,000 --> 00:06:51,000
 the world is perpetuating at them instead.

93
00:06:51,000 --> 00:06:53,000
 You see, in their context,

94
00:06:53,000 --> 00:06:56,000
 there's this thing known as the Colossian heresy.

95
00:06:56,000 --> 00:06:58,000
 And basically, it's a group of false teachers

96
00:06:58,000 --> 00:07:00,000
 that are looking at them and saying,

97
00:07:00,000 --> 00:07:03,000
 hey, if you want to find superior spirituality,

98
00:07:03,000 --> 00:07:06,000
 if you want to advance into a greater human experience,

99
00:07:06,000 --> 00:07:08,000
 add all this other stuff to your life.

100
00:07:08,000 --> 00:07:10,000
 Like believe in these different things.

101
00:07:10,000 --> 00:07:12,000
 Acquire this new knowledge.

102
00:07:12,000 --> 00:07:15,000
 And Paul is saying, as we transition from 1 to chapter 2,

103
00:07:15,000 --> 00:07:19,000
 looking at verse 3, he says, you don't have to do that.

104
00:07:19,000 --> 00:07:23,000
 Because in Christ are hidden all the treasures of wisdom and knowledge.

105
00:07:23,000 --> 00:07:25,000
 You don't need to look anywhere else.

106
00:07:25,000 --> 00:07:29,000
 If you want to grow and go forward,

107
00:07:29,000 --> 00:07:32,000
 the way you do it is by looking to him.

108
00:07:32,000 --> 00:07:34,000
 We've said this.

109
00:07:34,000 --> 00:07:38,000
 Maturity in life comes through clarity of Christ.

110
00:07:38,000 --> 00:07:43,000
 That's the big topic, the main theme of this entire book.

111
00:07:43,000 --> 00:07:47,000
 And as we move forward into the rest of Paul's letter,

112
00:07:47,000 --> 00:07:50,000
 he's going to begin to unpack for us

113
00:07:50,000 --> 00:07:53,000
 what specific lessons we need to learn

114
00:07:53,000 --> 00:07:57,000
 if we want to walk into the wholehearted fullness

115
00:07:57,000 --> 00:07:59,000
 that is available in Jesus.

116
00:07:59,000 --> 00:08:02,000
 So this is what he says, starting in verse 6.

117
00:08:02,000 --> 00:08:07,000
 "Therefore, in light of the fact that you do believe in him,

118
00:08:07,000 --> 00:08:10,000
 as you received Christ Jesus the Lord,

119
00:08:10,000 --> 00:08:14,000
 so walk in him, rooted and built up in him,

120
00:08:14,000 --> 00:08:17,000
 established in the faith, just as you were taught,

121
00:08:17,000 --> 00:08:19,000
 abounding in thanksgiving."

122
00:08:19,000 --> 00:08:22,000
 How does Paul choose to teach these young believers

123
00:08:22,000 --> 00:08:24,000
 the way of walking in Jesus?

124
00:08:24,000 --> 00:08:28,000
 How is he going to teach us the way of walking in Jesus?

125
00:08:28,000 --> 00:08:30,000
 In a really strategic way.

126
00:08:30,000 --> 00:08:32,000
 He looks at them and he says,

127
00:08:32,000 --> 00:08:35,000
 "Hey, you need to learn how to walk in him

128
00:08:35,000 --> 00:08:40,000
 by comparing it to the way in which you received him."

129
00:08:40,000 --> 00:08:42,000
 Which is a really great strategy

130
00:08:42,000 --> 00:08:44,000
 for teaching somebody something.

131
00:08:44,000 --> 00:08:46,000
 How do I do that?

132
00:08:46,000 --> 00:08:48,000
 Do this the way you did that.

133
00:08:48,000 --> 00:08:50,000
 The way you did X, now you go do Y.

134
00:08:50,000 --> 00:08:52,000
 That's what he's saying.

135
00:08:52,000 --> 00:08:54,000
 Which begs the question then,

136
00:08:54,000 --> 00:08:56,000
 how did they receive Christ?

137
00:08:56,000 --> 00:08:58,000
 With extreme care.

138
00:08:58,000 --> 00:09:00,000
 That's what they do.

139
00:09:00,000 --> 00:09:02,000
 They received Christ with extreme care.

140
00:09:02,000 --> 00:09:05,000
 Because Paul uses a term here that's interesting.

141
00:09:05,000 --> 00:09:07,000
 It's actually a technical word in Judaism

142
00:09:07,000 --> 00:09:09,000
 that refers to the transmission of teaching

143
00:09:09,000 --> 00:09:11,000
 from one person or generation to another.

144
00:09:11,000 --> 00:09:14,000
 So just think about that most beloved family recipe

145
00:09:14,000 --> 00:09:16,000
 that you have.

146
00:09:16,000 --> 00:09:18,000
 That thing which has been handed down

147
00:09:18,000 --> 00:09:21,000
 with painstaking care from one generation to the next.

148
00:09:21,000 --> 00:09:24,000
 What is it for you?

149
00:09:24,000 --> 00:09:28,000
 That is how they have received the good news of Jesus Christ.

150
00:09:28,000 --> 00:09:30,000
 With painstaking detail.

151
00:09:30,000 --> 00:09:32,000
 With meticulous care.

152
00:09:32,000 --> 00:09:34,000
 They haven't just received it carelessly.

153
00:09:34,000 --> 00:09:36,000
 They've received it carefully.

154
00:09:36,000 --> 00:09:38,000
 There's nothing casual about this.

155
00:09:38,000 --> 00:09:40,000
 They heard the good news of Jesus

156
00:09:40,000 --> 00:09:43,000
 and they received it with intense focus.

157
00:09:43,000 --> 00:09:45,000
 They wanted to learn.

158
00:09:45,000 --> 00:09:47,000
 They had heard the stories of this man.

159
00:09:47,000 --> 00:09:49,000
 They had read the reports of what he'd done.

160
00:09:49,000 --> 00:09:51,000
 They had even learned of his impact

161
00:09:51,000 --> 00:09:53,000
 in the lives of other people.

162
00:09:53,000 --> 00:09:55,000
 And they said, "We've received this.

163
00:09:55,000 --> 00:09:57,000
 So now what do we do?

164
00:09:57,000 --> 00:09:59,000
 We want to believe this.

165
00:09:59,000 --> 00:10:02,000
 So we've acquired great knowledge of these things."

166
00:10:02,000 --> 00:10:04,000
 You see, their lives were transformed

167
00:10:04,000 --> 00:10:06,000
 because their hearts were transfixed

168
00:10:06,000 --> 00:10:08,000
 on the one who would come to save them.

169
00:10:08,000 --> 00:10:11,000
 And, Ports, the same should be true for us.

170
00:10:11,000 --> 00:10:13,000
 Which is why it's really important

171
00:10:13,000 --> 00:10:15,000
 when we talk about faith in Jesus,

172
00:10:15,000 --> 00:10:17,000
 believing in God,

173
00:10:17,000 --> 00:10:20,000
 that we don't just pin our faith

174
00:10:20,000 --> 00:10:25,000
 on the basis of something really rather weak.

175
00:10:25,000 --> 00:10:27,000
 That's why it's not enough to believe in Christ

176
00:10:27,000 --> 00:10:29,000
 because your parents do.

177
00:10:29,000 --> 00:10:32,000
 Or to follow Jesus because it's socially advantageous

178
00:10:32,000 --> 00:10:34,000
 to do that here in the South.

179
00:10:34,000 --> 00:10:37,000
 It's a good way to meet people and find friends.

180
00:10:37,000 --> 00:10:39,000
 We don't walk with God

181
00:10:39,000 --> 00:10:41,000
 because our boyfriend or our girlfriend,

182
00:10:41,000 --> 00:10:44,000
 they kind of like him, and so I guess I should like him as well

183
00:10:44,000 --> 00:10:47,000
 because I want that relationship to sustain.

184
00:10:47,000 --> 00:10:51,000
 We don't follow him because we want to get out of hell free card.

185
00:10:51,000 --> 00:10:57,000
 These are all bad reasons to walk with Jesus.

186
00:10:57,000 --> 00:10:59,000
 Contrary to popular belief,

187
00:10:59,000 --> 00:11:03,000
 there are in fact bad testimonies out there.

188
00:11:03,000 --> 00:11:06,000
 What makes a bad testimony?

189
00:11:06,000 --> 00:11:09,000
 Not the absence of divine intervention.

190
00:11:09,000 --> 00:11:11,000
 "Man, there's not really like a burning bush

191
00:11:11,000 --> 00:11:13,000
 or a pillar of fire in my story."

192
00:11:13,000 --> 00:11:15,000
 That doesn't make a bad testimony.

193
00:11:15,000 --> 00:11:17,000
 There are loads of people like that.

194
00:11:17,000 --> 00:11:19,000
 What makes a bad testimony

195
00:11:19,000 --> 00:11:22,000
 is not the absence of divine intervention,

196
00:11:22,000 --> 00:11:28,000
 but the presence of personal indifference.

197
00:11:28,000 --> 00:11:31,000
 "I don't really care. He seems like a nice guy.

198
00:11:31,000 --> 00:11:34,000
 I guess I should religiously ascribe to someone.

199
00:11:34,000 --> 00:11:36,000
 It might as well be him."

200
00:11:36,000 --> 00:11:40,000
 Paul's saying, "You don't receive Christ like that."

201
00:11:40,000 --> 00:11:42,000
 That's not how they've received him.

202
00:11:42,000 --> 00:11:46,000
 They've received him with great care.

203
00:11:46,000 --> 00:11:49,000
 They are absolutely, utterly transformed

204
00:11:49,000 --> 00:11:55,000
 because they are totally transfixed on this man, Jesus Christ.

205
00:11:55,000 --> 00:11:57,000
 And the same should be true for us.

206
00:11:57,000 --> 00:12:02,000
 You see, we don't believe in Jesus because it's convenient.

207
00:12:02,000 --> 00:12:07,000
 We believe in Jesus because we're convinced.

208
00:12:07,000 --> 00:12:09,000
 We're convinced.

209
00:12:09,000 --> 00:12:12,000
 We've heard the facts of his life.

210
00:12:12,000 --> 00:12:14,000
 We've read the report ourselves.

211
00:12:14,000 --> 00:12:17,000
 We've beheld the beauty of his character.

212
00:12:17,000 --> 00:12:21,000
 We've observed the wonder of his nature.

213
00:12:21,000 --> 00:12:26,000
 And we've received his forgiveness firsthand.

214
00:12:26,000 --> 00:12:29,000
 And because we've done these things,

215
00:12:29,000 --> 00:12:32,000
 we can't help but believe.

216
00:12:32,000 --> 00:12:35,000
 We can't help but be spurned forward towards more.

217
00:12:35,000 --> 00:12:41,000
 And we can't help but want to learn as much as possible.

218
00:12:41,000 --> 00:12:44,000
 Paul is saying, in the same way that we've received him like that,

219
00:12:44,000 --> 00:12:50,000
 as undeniably true, like, "Man, I cannot refute the fact that this is all actually accurate."

220
00:12:50,000 --> 00:12:54,000
 The way that we've received him as that is the way we should walk in him.

221
00:12:54,000 --> 00:12:56,000
 You received him with great focus.

222
00:12:56,000 --> 00:12:59,000
 You should walk in him with great focus.

223
00:12:59,000 --> 00:13:01,000
 That's what he's saying.

224
00:13:01,000 --> 00:13:05,000
 As he moves through this, he moves from the indicative form to the imperative form.

225
00:13:05,000 --> 00:13:07,000
 Which just means he makes an indicative statement.

226
00:13:07,000 --> 00:13:09,000
 He indicates something that's true.

227
00:13:09,000 --> 00:13:11,000
 He makes a statement of fact.

228
00:13:11,000 --> 00:13:13,000
 You received Christ.

229
00:13:13,000 --> 00:13:15,000
 That's observable. That's factual.

230
00:13:15,000 --> 00:13:17,000
 We can say that that actually happened.

231
00:13:17,000 --> 00:13:19,000
 He moves from an indicative statement, you've received him,

232
00:13:19,000 --> 00:13:21,000
 to an imperative statement, which is a command.

233
00:13:21,000 --> 00:13:23,000
 So then do this.

234
00:13:23,000 --> 00:13:25,000
 That's where he moves as he goes along.

235
00:13:25,000 --> 00:13:32,000
 He says there's no hiatus between believing in Jesus and behaving like a Jesus follower.

236
00:13:32,000 --> 00:13:34,000
 They go hand in hand.

237
00:13:34,000 --> 00:13:36,000
 Their two sisters tied at the hip.

238
00:13:36,000 --> 00:13:38,000
 You place your faith, you walk in him.

239
00:13:38,000 --> 00:13:40,000
 It just goes together.

240
00:13:40,000 --> 00:13:42,000
 That's what he's unpacking for us.

241
00:13:42,000 --> 00:13:44,000
 Why? Why is that the case?

242
00:13:44,000 --> 00:13:46,000
 Because Jesus is not just a nice guy.

